Came here twice this month: weekend brunch and weeknight dinner. Both times, service was so slow after the first greeting. The food also took at least 20 minutes--even for appetizer (lumpia).  Lumpia Shanghai (brunch): good contrast of flavors between the spring roll and the pineapple sauce. The sauce also goes well with all the dishes. Portion was smaller than I expected with 4 rolls, cut in half for 8 pieces.  Pancit: the noodles had a really good bounce--not too mushy and not al dente.  Lechon: the weekend brunch portion is 6 pieces that are approx 2x2x2 big. It was nicely crispy and very oily but the pork meat was very tender. When I went on a weeknight, the price is almost double, and they give 4 pieces with one big piece (5") attached to the bone. The soy sauce dip isn't necessary since the meat has so much flavor. The carrot turnip slaw is very sour.  Cured pork garlic rice (dinner): 2 pretty sunny eggs to make a heart shape (not sure if intentional). The garlic rice was not as flavorful as my weekend brunch experience. The grilled cured pork was so good! (It reminded me of Vietnamese grilled pork.) It was pretty burnt though with black grill marks on 90% of one side.  Cured beef garlic rice (brunch): same dish as above with different protein. It was definitely NOT grilled to blackness and the garlic rice was much more pungent.  Buko pie (brunch): it wasn't overly sweet, which was a good surprise. It also had purple-ish colors. The mascarpone ice cream is 💯

Upset that we both felt nothing was good. It's authentic Filipino and Pan-Asian cooking. Chef Romy's interpretation of Filipino classics such as chicken adobo, bistec, and tocino are fantastic. It's different from my late grandmother's cooking but just as good and in some ways better. My family is from the Manila metro area so the cuisine is slightly different. Even though my parents are from a different part of the Philippines, we know good authentic pinoy food. Purple Yam is easily one of the best Filipino restaurants in NYC. All of my family heartily appreciate and approve of the food. All of the dishes are great, but it can be a little overwhelming to those unfamiliar with Filipino cuisine. Here are my recommendations for the newbies... For an appetizer start with the ukoy (deep fried veg-shrimp fritters) or lumpia Shanghai (egg rolls). For the entre, try the chicken adobo to start. For dessert order some halo-halo (mixture of shaved ice, milk, fruits, sweets) . Purple Yam concoction of this dessert is top notch. My favorite dessert is the champorado (chocolate rice porridge) with ice cream. With regards to beverages Chef Romy has a good selection of alcohol and soft drinks. In my opinion just go for the Calamansi juice. FYI, Calamansi is sort of a lemon lime orange hybrid. If you try it you will understand. It's good. You won't regret eating here. Prices are very reasonable.

Traveled 2 hours from Manhattan (subway service delays) each way and the food at Purple Yam was totally worth it.  If you are expecting very traditional Filipino food, perhaps this isn't the place for you.  What makes this place special is they serve Filipino food with a twist (influences of Korean, Malay, and other Asian influences) -- and boy do they get it right.  While the portion sizes aren't large, this is New York City, and I would say their portions are reasonable for the price (for NYC standards).  The desserts are the BEST.  Period.  You can't go wrong with any of them.  Overall, fantastic restaurant.  Just make sure you know what kind of Filipino restaurant you're signing up for (to manage your own expectation).
